The paper discusses holographic representations of data, which are particularly useful for distributed storage and transmission of data packets over networks with unpredictable delays and erasures. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses methods for holographic representations of signals and images, which suggests that it may also belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) and Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the use of least-squares estimation theory, which is commonly used in the Data Structures (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the transmission of data packets over networks, which suggests that it may also belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category.
